---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import SiteHeader from '../components/SiteHeader.astro';
import SiteFooter from '../components/SiteFooter.astro';
import SideNav from '../components/SideNav.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Portfolio">
  <SiteHeader />
  <SideNav />

  <main class="portfolio-main">
    <h1 class="portfolio-title">Portfolio</h1>

    <section class="project-section">
      <h2 class="project-heading">
        Cookie cutter<img class="cookie cookie--head" src="/images/portfolio/cookie.png" alt="" aria-hidden="true" />
      </h2>

      <div class="project-row">
        <div class="desc-col">
          <div class="project-box">
            <p>Cookies, stored by websites in your browser, and their contents are often deliberately scrambled so you can't tell what's being tracked. I built a browser extension that unscrambles and explains a site's cookies in plain language, and runs the entire analysis on your own device, so no cookie value is ever sent anywhere. This not only helps breakdown exactly what data is being shared and with whom, it also gives you the option to filter them to protect your data.</p>
            <img class="cookie cookie--below-desc" src="/images/portfolio/cookie.png" alt="" aria-hidden="true" />
          </div>

          <div class="project-box project-box--indent">
            <p>The demo lets you set how cookies are blocked, add trusted sites to an allowlist, and see quick stats on active, changed, and blocked cookies. The main list shows every cookie on the page with its category, a colour-coded risk rating, and its purpose — click one to see a plain-language explanation and its raw value. Below that, a live log tracks blocked cookie traffic, with buttons to refresh, clear the log, or open options.</p>
            <img class="cookie cookie--between" src="/images/portfolio/cookie.png" alt="" aria-hidden="true" />
            <img class="cookie cookie--below-demo" src="/images/portfolio/cookie.png" alt="" aria-hidden="true" />
          </div>

          <img class="demo-arrow" src="/images/portfolio/pink-arrow.png" alt="" aria-hidden="true" />
        </div>

        <div class="demo-wrapper">
          <iframe
            class="demo-frame demo-frame--dark"
            src="/demos/cookie-guard-dark.html"
            title="Cookie Guard Reporter — interactive demo (dark)"
            loading="lazy"
            sandbox="allow-scripts allow-same-origin"
          ></iframe>
          <iframe
            class="demo-frame demo-frame--light"
            src="/demos/cookie-guard-light.html"
            title="Cookie Guard Reporter — interactive demo (light)"
            loading="lazy"
            sandbox="allow-scripts allow-same-origin"
          ></iframe>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="project-box project-box--right">
        <p class="how-title">How does it do this?</p>
        <ul class="how-list">
          <li><strong>Fully offline</strong> — every cookie value is decoded and analysed locally in the browser; nothing is ever transmitted to an external service.</li>
          <li><strong>Multi-layer decoder</strong> — recognises and peels back up to four layers of encoding (URL, Base64, hexadecimal, JWT, and JSON, plus detection of binary Protocol Buffers data), since real tracking cookies are frequently wrapped several times over.</li>
          <li><strong>Content classifier</strong> — reads the decoded data for tell-tale signals like identifiers, analytics tags, and timestamps to sort each cookie into a category (functional, analytics, advertising) and assign a privacy-risk rating.</li>
          <li><strong>Known-tracker knowledge base</strong> — instantly recognises common trackers such as Google Analytics (_ga) and Meta (_fbp) and explains what they do.</li>
          <li><strong>Plain-language output</strong> — turns the whole analysis into a readable summary anyone can understand, while staying fast and private by capping values at 4,096 characters and limiting decoding to four passes.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="project-section">
      <h2 class="project-heading">SSH Brute-Force Intrusion Detection System</h2>

      <div class="ssh-row">
        <div class="ssh-images">
          <img class="ssh-img ssh-img--attack ssh-img--dark" src="/images/portfolio/attack_defense_dark.png" alt="Diagram: SSH brute-force attack and how detector.py defends against it" />
          <img class="ssh-img ssh-img--attack ssh-img--light" src="/images/portfolio/attack_defense_light.png" alt="Diagram: SSH brute-force attack and how detector.py defends against it" />
          <img class="ssh-img ssh-img--dark" src="/images/portfolio/terminal-dark.png" alt="Terminal output from detector.py flagging repeated brute-force attempts" />
          <img class="ssh-img ssh-img--light" src="/images/portfolio/terminal-light.png" alt="Terminal output from detector.py flagging repeated brute-force attempts" />
        </div>

        <div class="ssh-text">
          <div class="project-box">
            <p>Servers are constantly hit by automated attacks that guess passwords thousands of times until one works. I built a Python tool that watches a server's login records as they're written and catches these brute-force attacks in real time, then produces professional-grade alerts that drop straight into a security team's monitoring pipeline.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="project-box">
            <p class="how-title">How does it do this?</p>
            <ul class="how-list">
              <li><strong>Reads logs live</strong> — tails the server's authentication log as it's written, so detection happens in the moment rather than after the fact.</li>
              <li><strong>Sliding-window detection</strong> — for every source address it keeps a rolling 60-second history of failed logins (the same pattern used to spot bursts of fraud), and only raises an alarm when an address crosses five failures inside that window — so a mistyped password never triggers a false alert.</li>
              <li><strong>Structured JSON alerts</strong> — each detection is written out with the severity, the attacker's address, and the targeted account, in a machine-readable format ready for automated tooling.</li>
              <li><strong>MITRE ATT&amp;CK tagging</strong> — every alert is labelled T1110.001 (Password Guessing) using the industry-standard threat catalogue security teams rely on, so the output needs no translation.</li>
              <li><strong>Validated on a real system</strong> — tested against a live OpenSSH server on an Ubuntu 24.04 virtual machine, with simulated attacks and real logs captured from the system journal.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="project-section">
      <h2 class="project-heading">Lynra</h2>

      <div class="lynra-media">
        <img class="leaf leaf--1" src="/images/portfolio/leaf.png" alt="" aria-hidden="true" />
        <img class="leaf leaf--2" src="/images/portfolio/leaf.png" alt="" aria-hidden="true" />
        <img class="leaf leaf--3" src="/images/portfolio/leaf.png" alt="" aria-hidden="true" />
        <img
          class="lynra-img"
          src="/images/portfolio/lynra.png"
          alt="Photo collage of the Lynra team and their tree-injecting rover at Dogpatch Labs"
          width="1800"
          height="570"
          loading="lazy"
        />
      </div>

      <div class="lynra-row">
        <div class="lynra-text">
          <div class="project-box">
            <p>Ash dieback is a fungal disease killing ash trees across Ireland and Europe, and treating them by hand at scale isn't practical. As part of a four-person team at the Patch Summer Accelerator, I helped build Lynra: an autonomous rover that identifies ash trees and delivers a lifesaving biostimulant directly into them through a micro-injection, making large-scale treatment possible. We designed, prototyped, and 3D-printed the rover ourselves and presented it live at Demo Day to an audience of 300+ investors, founders, and industry leaders.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="project-box">
            <p class="how-title">How does it do this?</p>
            <ul class="how-list" id="lynra-how">
              <li><strong>AI tree detection</strong> — a custom object-detection and recognition model in Roboflow identifies the base of ash trees (the injection site) from the rover's camera feed in real time.</li>
              <li><strong>Onboard processing</strong> — the model runs on a Raspberry Pi mounted on the rover, letting it detect and make decisions based on the frames it analyses, which then instruct an Arduino that directly controls the rover's movements.</li>
              <li><strong>Automated micro-injection</strong> — once a target is identified, the rover positions itself and delivers a precise micro-dose of biostimulant into the tree using a needle, without damaging the trunk.</li>
              <li><strong>Custom-built hardware</strong> — the chassis and delivery system were designed in Fusion 360, prototyped, and 3D-printed in-house by the team.</li>
              <li><strong>Navigation</strong> — the rover is entirely autonomous, using the video feed to control its movements.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="lynra-zoom">
          <div class="zoom-stage" id="lynra-stage">
            <img
              class="zoom-img"
              id="lynra-img"
              src="/images/portfolio/lynra-rover.jpg"
              alt="The Lynra rover: a two-tier plywood chassis carrying a battery, control electronics, a Raspberry Pi, pneumatics and a 3D-printed syringe assembly, on four treaded wheels."
              width="1400"
              height="1614"
              loading="lazy"
            />
            <span class="zoom-reticle" id="lynra-reticle" aria-hidden="true">
              <b class="c1"></b><b class="c2"></b><b class="c3"></b><b class="c4"></b>
            </span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="project-section">
      <h2 class="project-heading">SÓShieldta</h2>
      <p class="project-subheading">Social Engineering Simulation Platform</p>

      <!-- Row 1: "What it does" (left) beside the landing-page screenshot (right). -->
      <div class="so-row">
        <div class="so-text">
          <div class="project-box">
            <p class="how-title">What it does</p>
            <p>Most people only get static security training, so their first real social-engineering attack is often a live one that breaches their company. SÓShieldta lets organisations safely run realistic simulated attacks against their own staff to test and improve how well they spot and react to them, with a dashboard that tracks results and flags who needs more training. As the only cybersecurity student on our four-person team, I was able to bring a technical insight to the most current attack surfaces we should be protecting, and the current attack vectors to protect against. The entire project was built in 30 hours at HackEurope 2026.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="so-media">
          <img
            class="so-img"
            src="/images/portfolio/soshieldta-landing.png"
            alt="The SÓShieldta landing page: the tagline 'Security starts with people' above a feature grid covering AI-powered attacks, employee risk scoring, multi-channel vectors, and automated remediation."
            width="1905"
            height="1077"
            loading="lazy"
          />
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Row 2: dashboard screenshot (left) beside "How does it do this?" (right). -->
      <div class="so-row so-row--flip">
        <div class="so-media so-media--stack">
          <img
            class="so-img"
            src="/images/portfolio/soshieldta-dashboard.png"
            alt="The SÓShieldta security dashboard: risk score, campaigns run, failure rate and reporting rate, a per-channel breakdown for email, SMS, WhatsApp and voice, campaign analytics charts, and a recent test activity feed."
            width="1907"
            height="1079"
            loading="lazy"
          />
          <img
            class="so-img"
            src="/images/portfolio/soshieldta-campaign.png"
            alt="A SÓShieldta campaign's test results: a per-employee timeline showing the phishing email being generated and sent, the employee's reply, and the AI evaluation flagging that they fell for it and shared confidential information."
            width="1905"
            height="1076"
            loading="lazy"
          />
        </div>

        <div class="so-text">
          <div class="project-box">
            <p class="how-title">How does it do this?</p>
            <ul class="how-list">
              <li><strong>Context-driven attacks</strong> — organisations upload details like org charts and their tech stack, which the platform uses to generate lures tailored to each employee's role, so simulations feel convincing rather than obviously fake.</li>
              <li><strong>Multi-channel simulation</strong> — attacks arrive across the surfaces real attackers use: phishing email, smishing (SMS), and vishing (AI voice calls).</li>
              <li><strong>Realistic AI content</strong> — because mainstream models refuse to write phishing, lures and call scripts are generated through an open model, producing unique campaigns that don't pattern-match as spam.</li>
              <li><strong>AI voice calls</strong> — vishing uses ElevenLabs for a convincing synthetic voice, with Twilio as a fallback for calls and texts.</li>
              <li><strong>Closed-loop training</strong> — employees who fail get an instant targeted lesson and are prompted to write back to their employer on what they learned, replacing tick-box quizzes with real reflection.</li>
              <li><strong>Built for scale</strong> — a Supabase backend and tiered Stripe billing make it work as a real multi-organisation product.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="project-section">
      <div class="mc-banner">
        <img
          class="mc-car"
          src="/images/portfolio/moving-clean-logo.png"
          alt=""
          aria-hidden="true"
        />
        <h2 class="project-heading">Moving Clean</h2>
        <p class="project-subheading">Carbon-Capture Exhaust Filter</p>
      </div>

      <div class="mc-row">
        <div class="mc-text">
          <div class="project-box">
            <p>An award-winning device developed through Teen Turn that won the SciFest Technology Category and the EirGrid Award, with national press coverage in the Irish Independent, CorkBeo, and IrishCentral.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="project-box">
            <p class="how-title">What it does</p>
            <p>Cars burning fossil fuels are one of the largest drivers of climate change. Moving Clean is a filter designed to fit onto a car's exhaust and strip carbon dioxide out of its emissions before it reaches the air, splitting it into carbon that's safely stored and oxygen that's released back out — with the goal of making everyday driving far less damaging to the environment.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="project-box">
            <p class="how-title">How does it do this?</p>
            <ul class="how-list">
              <li><strong>Direct Air Capture</strong> — adapts an existing technology that uses chemical reactions to pull CO₂ out of exhaust gas, rather than letting it escape into the atmosphere.</li>
              <li><strong>Heat-driven separation</strong> — heat forces the CO₂ molecule to split into carbon and oxygen; the oxygen is released and the carbon is captured.</li>
              <li><strong>Safe onboard storage</strong> — the separated carbon is held in a cylinder mounted under the car, safe near the engine because carbon combusts only at 300–450°C.</li>
              <li><strong>Reusable output</strong> — the captured carbon isn't just waste: it can be repurposed as a feedstock for industrial materials or to support plant growth, closing the loop.</li>
              <li><strong>Designed and built</strong> — developed as a working concept with 3D printing and CAD as part of a four-person team.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Sticky live CAD viewer: drag to orbit, scroll to zoom, auto-rotates when idle. -->
        <div class="mc-viewer">
          <div class="mc-stage">
            <model-viewer
              src="/models/moving-clean.glb"
              alt="Interactive 3D model of the Moving Clean carbon-capture exhaust filter — drag to rotate it."
              camera-controls
              touch-action="pan-y"
              auto-rotate
              auto-rotate-delay="1200"
              rotation-per-second="18deg"
              camera-orbit="35deg 72deg auto"
              interaction-prompt="none"
              shadow-intensity="0.6"
              exposure="1"
              loading="lazy"
              reveal="auto"
            >
              <div class="mc-poster" slot="poster">Loading model…</div>
              <div class="mc-hint" slot="progress-bar"></div>
            </model-viewer>
          </div>
          <p class="mc-caption">Drag to swivel · scroll to zoom</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>

  <SiteFooter />
</BaseLayout>

<!-- <model-viewer> web component: gives the CAD model orbit / zoom / auto-rotate.
     Loaded from a CDN as a module, the same way the fonts come from Google. -->
<script
  is:inline
  type="module"
  src="https://unpkg.com/@google/model-viewer@4.3.1/dist/model-viewer.min.js"
></script>

<script>
  window.addEventListener('load', () => {
    const box = document.querySelector<HTMLElement>('.desc-col > .project-box');
    const frames = document.querySelectorAll<HTMLElement>('.demo-frame');
    if (box && frames.length) {
      const h = `${box.getBoundingClientRect().height * 2}px`;
      frames.forEach((frame) => { frame.style.height = h; });
    }
  });
</script>

<script>
  // Lynra: scroll-driven zoom. Each <li> in the "How does it do this?" list
  // focuses a different part of the rover in the sticky image beside it.
  const stage = document.getElementById('lynra-stage');
  const zoomImg = document.getElementById('lynra-img') as HTMLImageElement | null;
  const reticle = document.getElementById('lynra-reticle');
  const list = document.getElementById('lynra-how');

  if (stage && zoomImg && reticle && list) {
    const items = Array.from(list.querySelectorAll('li'));

    // fx/fy = focal point (fraction of the image), z = zoom, box = lock-on rect.
    // Index 0 is the resting wide shot; 1–5 map to the five list items in order.
    const KF = [
      { fx: 0.480, fy: 0.51, z: 1.00, box: [0.04, 0.09, 0.84, 0.84] },
      { fx: 0.436, fy: 0.50, z: 2.10, box: [0.24, 0.40, 0.36, 0.22] }, // AI tree detection
      { fx: 0.762, fy: 0.45, z: 2.45, box: [0.64, 0.34, 0.24, 0.22] }, // Onboard processing
      { fx: 0.680, fy: 0.19, z: 2.35, box: [0.54, 0.09, 0.28, 0.19] }, // Automated micro-injection
      { fx: 0.471, fy: 0.20, z: 1.90, box: [0.18, 0.07, 0.58, 0.24] }, // Custom-built hardware
      { fx: 0.480, fy: 0.51, z: 1.12, box: [0.04, 0.09, 0.84, 0.84] }, // Navigation
    ];

    const IW = 1400;
    const IH = 1614;
    const reduce = window.matchMedia('(prefers-reduced-motion: reduce)').matches;
    const EASE = 'transform 0.7s cubic-bezier(.22,.61,.36,1)';

    let current = 0;
    let shown = -1;

    const clamp = (v: number, a: number, b: number) => Math.max(a, Math.min(b, v));

    function apply(index: number) {
      const w = stage!.clientWidth;
      const h = stage!.clientHeight;
      if (!w || !h) return;

      const kf = KF[clamp(index, 0, KF.length - 1)];
      const fit = Math.min(w / IW, h / IH);
      const scale = fit * kf.z;
      const left = w / 2 - kf.fx * IW * scale;
      const top = h / 2 - kf.fy * IH * scale;

      zoomImg!.style.transition = reduce ? 'none' : EASE;
      zoomImg!.style.transform = `translate(${left}px, ${top}px) scale(${scale})`;

      const [bx, by, bw, bh] = kf.box;
      reticle!.style.transition = reduce ? 'none' : 'all 0.7s cubic-bezier(.22,.61,.36,1)';
      reticle!.style.left = `${left + bx * IW * scale}px`;
      reticle!.style.top = `${top + by * IH * scale}px`;
      reticle!.style.width = `${bw * IW * scale}px`;
      reticle!.style.height = `${bh * IH * scale}px`;
      reticle!.style.opacity = index === 0 ? '0' : '0.9';
    }

    // Active item = whichever list item sits nearest the middle of the viewport.
    function update() {
      const mid = window.innerHeight * 0.5;
      let best = -1;
      let dist = Infinity;

      items.forEach((li, i) => {
        const r = li.getBoundingClientRect();
        if (r.bottom < 0 || r.top > window.innerHeight) return;
        const d = Math.abs(r.top + r.height / 2 - mid);
        if (d < dist) { dist = d; best = i; }
      });

      current = best === -1 ? 0 : best + 1;
      items.forEach((li, i) => li.classList.toggle('is-active', i === best));

      if (current !== shown) {
        shown = current;
        apply(current);
      }
    }

    let ticking = false;
    const onScroll = () => {
      if (ticking) return;
      ticking = true;
      requestAnimationFrame(() => { update(); ticking = false; });
    };

    window.addEventListener('scroll', onScroll, { passive: true });
    window.addEventListener('resize', () => apply(current));

    if (zoomImg.complete) {
      apply(0);
      update();
    } else {
      zoomImg.addEventListener('load', () => { apply(0); update(); });
    }
  }
</script>

<style>
  /* Dark mode (default — no data-theme attribute) */
  :global(body) {
    background-image: url('/images/portfolio/bg-dark.svg');
    background-repeat: repeat;
    background-size: calc(100% / 6) auto;
    background-color: #000000;
  }

  /* Light mode */
  :global([data-theme="light"] body) {
    background-image: url('/images/portfolio/bg.svg');
    background-size: calc(100% / 6) auto;
    background-color: #ffffff;
  }

  /* Float the header over the grid — no white bar, no space taken in flow */
  :global(.site-header) {
    position: fixed;
    top: 0;
    left: 0;
    background-color: transparent !important;
    z-index: 100;
  }

  /* ── Layout ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */
  .portfolio-main {
    min-height: 100svh;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    padding-bottom: var(--space-16);
  }

  .portfolio-title {
    font-family: 'Press Start 2P', cursive;
    font-size: calc(var(--text-2xl) * 1.5);
    font-weight: 400;
    color: #ffe4c4;
    text-align: center;
    margin-top: var(--space-16);
    -webkit-text-stroke: 2px #000000;
    paint-order: stroke fill;
  }

  /* ── Project section ───────────────────────────────────────────────── */
  .project-section {
    width: 100%;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: var(--space-8);
    margin-top: 20vh;
  }

  .project-heading {
    font-family: 'Press Start 2P', cursive;
    font-size: calc(var(--text-2xl) * 1.5);
    font-weight: 400;
    color: #f699cd;
    text-align: center;
    -webkit-text-stroke: 2px #000000;
    paint-order: stroke fill;
  }

  /* ── Text boxes ────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */
  .project-box {
    background-color: #FF69B4;
    padding: var(--space-6);
    max-width: 600px;
    line-height: 1.8;
    font-size: var(--text-base);
    color: #ffffff;
  }

  /* Light mode: black text, lighter box colour */
  :global([data-theme="light"]) .project-box {
    color: #000000;
    background-color: #f699cd;
  }

  /* ── Cookie cutter: scattered cookie emojis ────────────────────────── */

  /* Anchor for the cookie tucked under the description box. */
  .desc-col > .project-box:first-child {
    position: relative;
  }

  .cookie {
    width: 52px;
    height: auto;
    pointer-events: none;
    user-select: none;
  }

  /* 1. Sits inline to the right of the heading, so the pair stays centred. */
  .cookie--head {
    display: inline-block;
    vertical-align: middle;
    margin-left: var(--space-4);
    transform: rotate(-10deg) translateY(-4px);
  }

  /* The remaining three are absolute ⇒ they take up no layout space and can't
     push the carefully-tuned demo/arrow offsets around. */
  .cookie--below-desc,
  .cookie--between,
  .cookie--below-demo {
    position: absolute;
    z-index: 2;
  }

  /* 2. Below the first (description) box, near its left edge. */
  .cookie--below-desc {
    bottom: -46px;
    left: var(--space-8);
    width: 58px;
    transform: rotate(14deg);
  }

  /* 3. Off the right of the demo box — the gap it shares with the
     "How does it do this?" box sitting below-right of it. */
  .cookie--between {
    top: 46%;
    right: -72px;
    width: 46px;
    transform: rotate(-22deg);
  }

  /* 4. Below the demo box. */
  .cookie--below-demo {
    bottom: -52px;
    left: 28%;
    width: 54px;
    transform: rotate(6deg);
  }

  @media (max-width: 900px) {
    .cookie {
      width: 36px;
    }

    .cookie--below-desc { width: 40px; bottom: -32px; }
    .cookie--between    { width: 32px; right: -44px; }
    .cookie--below-demo { width: 38px; bottom: -34px; }
  }

  /* ── Description + demo row ────────────────────────────────────────── */
  .project-row {
    display: flex;
    gap: var(--space-8);
    padding: 0 var(--space-6);
    align-items: flex-start;
    width: 100%;
  }

  /* Left column holds the description; also the positioning context for the
     floated demo-explanation box below it. */
  .desc-col {
    flex: 1;
    max-width: 600px;
    position: relative;
  }

  .desc-col > .project-box {
    max-width: 600px;
    margin: 0;
  }

  .demo-wrapper {
    flex: 1;
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    align-items: flex-start;
  }

  .demo-frame {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 600px;
    height: 300px; /* set to 2× text box height by script below */
    min-height: 300px;
    border: none;
  }

  /* Show the demo that matches the active theme — dark is the default. */
  .demo-frame--light {
    display: none;
  }

  :global([data-theme="light"]) .demo-frame--dark {
    display: none;
  }

  :global([data-theme="light"]) .demo-frame--light {
    display: block;
  }

  .project-box--left {
    align-self: flex-start;
    margin-left: var(--space-6);
  }

  .project-box--right {
    align-self: flex-end;
    margin-right: var(--space-6);
  }

